I attended the Borland World Tour specifically to find out about Delphi 
(and a little about InterBase).  At this point I am still a victim of 
sales hype, but it's based on first person observation, and I did 
actually SEE a demo of the product.

1) Delphi produces DLL's and EXE's.  You won't need a run time exe to 
run applications developed under Delphi.  They claim that the apps will 
run considerably faster than comparable Paradox apps (seems reasonable, 
but I couldn't verify).

2) In many ways Delphi is a lot closer to the Borland C++ product with 
the addition that a lot of work has been done to ease the job of 
creating, and maintaining the GUI.  It was VERY impressive, and on a 
DX4/100 portable appeared VERY fast.  Browsers and other tools and devt 
models appeared very comprehensive and powerful.

3) Delphi will come with a fairly comprehesive class library for the GUI 
which is truely object oriented.

4) Delphi is a compiled environment, but once again, compilation seemed 
MUCH faster than other environments I've used (i.e. Borland C++ and 
ObjectWindows).

5) Delphi is based on a version of OO-Pascal (It's a curious choice, 
maybe even disastrous, but at this point I'll try to be open minded).

6) Delphi can work with the Borland Data Base Engine, i.e. Paradox DB's, 
and Interbase.

7) Lastly, Delphi is truely Object Oriented.  OPAL does a pretty good 
job of integrating a robust event-model, and allows encapsulation.  
Delphi will, in addition, provide true inheritance (sub-classing), and 
polymorphism.  A good developer can really leverage this stuff.



