I have no qualms with your points, I just don't think it goes to the 
heart of the question.  The large issue is Delphi's potential market 
share!  If Borland doesn't crack the market in a big way with Delphi, 
then ...  At this stage of the game I am really pulling for Borland's 
survival.  They have historically upped the standard for PC based 
development tools and I believe the ongoing presence of Borland as a 
serious competitor to M-Soft is necessary if we are to continue to enjoy 
the availability of high quality, low(er) cost tools.

To this end, the usage of Pascal as the foundation language of Delphi 
presents a perceived cost associated with its' adoption, especially for 
orgs with existing custom software apps.  Borland needs to acquire 
serious market share in the commercial devt tool market to be 
successful.  If Delphi shortens devt cycles, improves maintainability, 
and reduces app resource consumption (as claimed) then, maybe, the 
company will achieve their past levels of success.


