I, for one, do not perceive the use of Pascal as a cost rather than an asset.  
Pascal in many aspects is much more sophisticated and powerful than Basic.  
It has been used for commercial application development for years, and is very 
mature in the hands of Borland.  Technically, Delphi has a lot of merits and 
should become a serious contender.

More important is, the choice of language is becoming less and less important 
in the application development arena.  The differences among various versions 
of Basic is just as great as the differences between Basic and Pascal, or C.  
I think people are caring less and less about whether it is C or Pascal or 
Basic, or even whether it is Powerscript or ObjectPal.  But people do care 
about whether it is data-smart, event-driven, object-oriented, etc.  In other 
worlds, syntax doesn't matter, but paradigm does.

If Delphi manages to obtain endorsement from several influential players in 
the industry, it will be successful.  Whether Borland can do that depends a 
lot on marketing.

